### Summary

Root Cause: When an mp4 file has a stco/co64 atom with entries=0, the
code still tries to read and write chunk offset data that doesn't exist.

### Details

An attacker controlled mp4 file can cause an OOB read followed by an OOB
write in both `ngx_http_mp4_update_stco_atom` and
`ngx_http_mp4_update_co64_atom`. When an stco or co64 atom has
entries=0, the code still unconditionally reads the first chunk_offset
from the buffer.

Below is the vulnerable code:

```c
     data->pos += trak->start_chunk * sizeof(uint32_t);

     chunk_offset = ngx_mp4_get_32value(data->pos);          // OOB READ
     samples_size = trak->start_chunk_samples_size;

     if (chunk_offset > (uint64_t) mp4->end - samples_size
         || chunk_offset + samples_size > NGX_MAX_UINT32_VALUE)
     {
         ngx_log_error(NGX_LOG_ERR, mp4->file.log, 0,
                       "too large chunk offset in \"%s\"",
                       mp4->file.name.data);
         return NGX_ERROR;
     }

     trak->start_offset = chunk_offset + samples_size;
     ngx_mp4_set_32value(data->pos, trak->start_offset);             //
OOB WRITE
```

### PoC

This can be triggered on the latest version of nginx using any config
that serves attacker-controlled mp4 files. Example config:
```
worker_processes 1;
daemon off;
error_log /dev/stderr debug;

events {}

http {
     access_log /dev/stdout;

     server {
         listen 8080;
         server_name localhost;

         location /videos/ {
             alias /srv/videos/;
             mp4;
         }
     }
}
```


