MariaDB’s JSON schema validation logic (`JSON_SCHEMA_VALID`) contains a heap overflow when parsing crafted enum definitions stored in user variables. By grooming user-defined variables on the server heap, an attacker can partially overwrite adjacent metadata, pivot a user-variable value pointer to arbitrary process memory, and read/write privileged structures without authentication bypass.
`json_get_normalized_string` allocates a local `DYNAMIC_STRING` via `init_dynamic_string(&a_res, NULL, 0, 0)` (default capacity 128) and copies `je->value_len` bytes into `a_res.str` with `strncpy` when normalizing JSON strings. Long string inputs exceed the fixed 128-byte buffer, causing a heap overflow.

```c++
void json_get_normalized_string(json_engine_t *je, String *res,
                                int *error, MEM_ROOT *current_mem_root,
                                json_engine_t *temp_je,
                                MEM_ROOT_DYNAMIC_ARRAY *stack)
{
  ...
  DYNAMIC_STRING a_res;

  if (init_dynamic_string(&a_res, NULL, 0, 0))
    goto error;
  ...
  else if(je->value_type == JSON_VALUE_STRING)
  {
    strncpy((char*)a_res.str, val.ptr(), je->value_len);
    a_res.length= je->value_len;
  }
  ...
}
```
`mariadb/mariadb-server/sql/json_schema_helper.cc:33-77`

